I need to prove this formula $$\sin x\cos y+\cos x\sin y=\sin(x+y)$$ using sums $$\sin x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^n\cdot x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}$$ $$\cos x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^n\cdot x^{2n}}{2n!}$$ My attempt to solve it: $$
\begin{align}
& \phantom{{}={}}\sin x\cos y+\cos x\sin y \\[10pt]
& =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^n\cdot x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^n\cdot y^{2n}}{2n!}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^n\cdot x^{2n}}{2n!}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^n\cdot y^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!} \\[10pt]
& =\sum_{n}^{\infty }\sum_{k}^{n}\frac{(-1)^kx^{2k+1}}{(2k+1)!}\frac{(-1)^{n-k}y^{2(n-k)}}{2(n-k)!}+\sum_{n}^{\infty }\sum_{k}^{n}\frac{(-1)^kx^{2k}}{2k!}\frac{(-1)^{n-k}y^{2(n-k)+1}}{(2(n-k)+1)!} \\[10pt]
& =\text{ ?}
\end{align}
$$ Now I don't know how to continue. I tried to do some "magic" with binomial coefficients but it wasnt successful. Thanks for help

This is an exercise in Apostol Calculus Vol.1 E6.22 Q.16. Let $\,f(x)=\sqrt{x} - \arctan \sqrt{x}.\;$ Then $$\begin{align} f'(x) &= \frac{1}{2 \sqrt{x}}- \frac{1}{1+(\sqrt{x})^2} \frac{1} 
{2\sqrt{x}}
\\&= \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}} \frac {1+x-1}{1+x}
\\&= \frac {1} {2\sqrt{x}} \frac{x}{1+x}
\\&= \frac{\sqrt{x}}{2(1+x)}
\end{align}$$ The answer from the textbook said it's valid if $x\geq0$, but we cancel out $\sqrt{x}$ when deriving $f'(x)$. I don't know why it's valid when $x=0$, so I hope someone could give me an explanation. Thanks.
